{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_016w9PpE7sPaJv5ewvNm1DGf","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tstepsCompleted: [1, 2, 3, 4]\n3\tstatus: 'complete'\n4\tcompletedAt: '2026-04-02'\n5\tinputDocuments:\n6\t  - prd-evaluator-redesign.md\n7\t  - architecture-v2.md\n8\t  - research/domain-harness-design-long-running-agents-research-2026-04-01.md\n9\t  - research/technical-workflow-engine-implementation-research-2026-04-02.md\n10\t---\n11\t\n12\t# codeharness v2 - Epic Breakdown\n13\t\n14\t## Overview\n15\t\n16\tThis document provides the complete epic and story breakdown for codeharness v2, decomposing 49 FRs, 18 NFRs, and 6 architectural decisions into implementable stories.\n17\t\n18\t## Requirements Inventory\n19\t\n20\t### Functional Requirements\n21\t\n22\t- FR1: User can define a workflow as a YAML file with tasks, flow order, and loop blocks\n23\t- FR2: User can specify per-task properties: agent assignment, scope, session boundary, source access, input/output contracts, prompt template\n24\t- FR3: User can define flow execution order as an ordered list of task references\n25\t- FR4: User can define loop steps using a loop: block containing an ordered list of tasks to repeat\n26\t- FR5: System validates workflow YAML against a JSON schema at parse time and rejects malformed definitions\n27\t- FR6: System ships a default embedded workflow for standard BMAD sprint execution\n28\t- FR7: System ships 9 embedded agents: dev, qa, architect, pm, sm, analyst, ux-designer, tech-writer, evaluator\n29\t- FR8: User can create custom agents at project level or user level\n30\t- FR9: User can patch embedded or user-level agents via extends with structured overrides and prompt_patches\n31\t- FR10: Agent config supports BMAD-compatible base fields and optional PersonaNexus-compatible traits\n32\t- FR11: System resolves agent config through embedded → user → project patch chain at runtime\n33\t- FR12: System compiles resolved agent config into Claude Code inline subagent definition\n34\t- FR13: User can create custom workflows at project level or user level\n35\t- FR14: User can patch embedded or user-level workflows via extends with structured overrides\n36\t- FR15: System resolves workflow config through embedded → user → project patch chain at runtime\n37\t- FR16: System reads resolved workflow and sprint-status.yaml to drive execution\n38\t- FR17: System executes per-story tasks once for each story in the sprint\n39\t- FR18: System executes per-run tasks once after all stories complete\n40\t- FR19: System dispatches agents via programmatic API with compiled subagent definitions\n41\t- FR20: System spawns fresh sessions or continues existing ones based on task session boundary config\n42\t- FR21: System passes defined input contracts to each task and collects defined outputs\n43\t- FR22: System generates a unique trace ID per iteration and injects it into agent prompts\n44\t- FR23: System enforces source_access: false by spawning the agent in a workspace with no source code\n45\t- FR24: System spawns a blind evaluator agent that exercises the built artifact via Docker and observability\n46\t- FR25: Evaluator reads ACs in user language and independently determines how to test each one\n47\t- FR26: Evaluator produces a structured JSON verdict with per-AC scores, status, evidence, findings\n48\t- FR27: Evaluator has access to story ACs, Docker container, observability — but not source code\n49\t- FR28: System re-verifies the entire artifact from scratch on each verification pass\n50\t- FR29: System injects evaluator findings into the retry task's agent prompt\n51\t- FR30: System filters retry execution to only stories the evaluator flagged as failed\n52\t- FR31: System executes flow loop steps until all ACs pass or circuit breaker triggers\n53\t- FR32: System tracks evaluator scores across iterations and detects score stagnation\n54\t- FR33: Circuit breaker triggers when evaluator scores stop improving\n55\t- FR34: System reports circuit breaker state with specific failures and score history\n56\t- FR35: User can resume execution after circuit breaker with manual fixes applied\n57\t- FR36: System generates and injects trace IDs that correlate across iteration, prompt, logs, metrics, traces\n58\t- FR37: Evaluator can query observability endpoints during verification\n59\t- FR38: User can create issues via codeharness issue create with optional priority and source\n60\t- FR39: System stores issues in issues.yaml with id, title, source, priority, status\n61\t- FR40: System reads both sprint-status.yaml and issues.yaml during workflow execution\n62\t- FR41: Issues use the same status values and execution path as stories\n63\t- FR42: Retro findings tagged as actionable are automatically added to issues.yaml\n64\t- FR43: User can run codeharness init to detect stack, generate default workflow, set up project\n65\t- FR44: User can run codeharness run to execute the workflow\n66\t- FR45: User can run codeharness validate to check workflow and agent YAML against schemas\n67\t- FR46: User can run codeharness status to see progress, evaluator scores, circuit breaker state\n68\t- FR47: User can run codeharness issue to create, list, and manage issues\n69\t- FR48: System does not contain Ralph bash loop, session flags, proof parsers, self-verify hooks, beads\n70\t- FR49: System has exactly one verification path: blind evaluator session\n71\t\n72\t### Non-Functional Requirements\n73\t\n74\t- NFR1: Workflow YAML parsing and validation in <500ms\n75\t- NFR2: Agent config resolution in <200ms\n76\t- NFR3: Agent session spawn in <5s excluding model response\n77\t- NFR4: Circuit breaker evaluation in <100ms\n78\t- NFR5: codeharness status returns in <1s\n79\t- NFR6: Engine state survives crashes — resume from last completed task\n80\t- NFR7: Evaluator timeout is scored failure, not fatal error\n81\t- NFR8: All state persisted after each task completion\n82\t- NFR9: Engine handles agent dispatch API errors gracefully\n83\t- NFR10: 4+ hour executions do not degrade or leak\n84\t- NFR11: Official programmatic agent dispatch API — no CLI spawning\n85\t- NFR12: BMAD agent configs read-only\n86\t- NFR13: Docker lifecycle managed by engine\n87\t- NFR14: Observability stack optional — graceful degradation\n88\t- NFR15: 80%+ unit test coverage on new modules\n89\t- NFR16: Zero shell scripts in execution path\n90\t- NFR17: Net negative LOC after legacy removal\n91\t- NFR18: Explicit TypeScript types, no any in API surface\n92\t\n93\t### Additional Requirements\n94\t\n95\t**From Architecture:**\n96\t- 7 modules in dependency order: workflow-state → workflow-parser → agent-resolver → agent-dispatch → workflow-engine → evaluator → circuit-breaker\n97\t- Evaluator workspace: temp dir, bare: true, disallowedTools: [Edit, Write]\n98\t- Embedded templates in templates/agents/ and templates/workflows/\n99\t- Config cached at startup\n100\t- Verdict enforced by JSON schema\n101\t- issues.yaml replaces beads\n102\t- 12 files need beads import cleanup\n103\t- ~40 files deleted (ralph/, hooks/, 8 lib, 3 templates)\n104\t- 13 commands reworked, 1 deleted, 3 kept\n105\t- 3 skills reworked, plugin.json updated\n106\t\n107\t**From Research:**\n108\t- Agent SDK query() as execution substrate\n109\t- loop: block syntax for flows\n110\t- BMAD → SDK inline subagent at runtime\n111\t- Evaluator judges subjectively, no contracts\n112\t- Anti-leniency: evidence per verdict\n113\t\n114\t### FR Coverage Map\n115\t\n116\t| FR | Epic | Description |\n117\t|----|------|-------------|\n118\t| FR1-6 | Epic 2 | Workflow definition, YAML schema, default workflow |\n119\t| FR7-12 | Epic 3 | Agent config, embedded agents, patching, resolution |\n120\t| FR13-15 | Epic 9 | Workflow config patching and resolution |\n121\t| FR16-18 | Epic 5 | Execution engine, per-story/per-run scope |\n122\t| FR19-23 | Epic 4 | Agent dispatch, sessions, trace IDs, source isolation |\n123\t| FR24-28 | Epic 6 | Blind evaluator, subjective verification, JSON verdict |\n124\t| FR29-31 | Epic 5 | Feedback loop, finding injection, loop execution |\n125\t| FR32-35 | Epic 7 | Circuit breaker, score stagnation, resume |\n126\t| FR36 | Epic 4 | Trace ID generation and injection |\n127\t| FR37 | Epic 6 | Evaluator observability queries |\n128\t| FR38-39, FR42 | Epic 8 | Issue create, store, retro auto-import |\n129\t| FR40-41 | Epic 5 | Engine reads issues.yaml alongside sprint-status |\n130\t| FR43 | Epic 2 | codeharness init |\n131\t| FR44 | Epic 5 | codeharness run |\n132\t| FR45 | Epic 2 | codeharness validate |\n133\t| FR46 | Epic 5 | codeharness status |\n134\t| FR47 | Epic 8 | codeharness issue |\n135\t| FR48-49 | Epic 1 | Legacy removal |\n136\t\n137\t## Epic List\n138\t\n139\t### Epic 1: Legacy Cleanup & Foundation\n140\tDeveloper has a clean codebase — beads removed, legacy files deleted, workflow-state module as foundation.\n141\t**FRs:** FR48, FR49 | **NFRs:** NFR16, NFR17\n142\t\n143\t### Epic 2: Workflow Definition & Validation\n144\tDeveloper can author workflow YAML, validate it, and init generates a default workflow.\n145\t**FRs:** FR1-6, FR43, FR45 | **NFRs:** NFR1\n146\t\n147\t### Epic 3: Agent Configuration System\n148\t9 embedded agents available. Custom agents and patches at project/user level. Config resolution chain.\n149\t**FRs:** FR7-12 | **NFRs:** NFR2, NFR12\n150\t\n151\t### Epic 4: Agent Dispatch & Session Management\n152\tEngine spawns Claude Code sessions via Agent SDK with session boundaries, trace IDs, and source isolation.\n153\t**FRs:** FR19-23, FR36 | **NFRs:** NFR3, NFR11\n154\t\n155\t### Epic 5: Workflow Execution Engine\n156\t`codeharness run` executes the workflow — per-story tasks, per-run tasks, loop blocks, finding injection. Reads stories and issues.\n157\t**FRs:** FR13-18, FR29-31, FR40-41, FR44, FR46 | **NFRs:** NFR6-10\n158\t\n159\t### Epic 6: Blind Evaluator & Verification\n160\tBlind evaluator exercises artifact, produces JSON verdict with per-AC evidence, engine handles retry loop.\n161\t**FRs:** FR24-28, FR37 | **NFRs:** NFR7, NFR13, NFR14\n162\t\n163\t### Epic 7: Circuit Breaker & Progress Detection\n164\tScore-based stagnation detection, halt on no-progress, specific failure reporting, resume after manual fixes.\n165\t**FRs:** FR32-35 | **NFRs:** NFR4\n166\t\n167\t### Epic 8: Issue Tracking & Retro Integration\n168\t`codeharness issue` CLI for create/list/manage. Retro findings auto-import. Issues execute alongside stories.\n169\t**FRs:** FR38-39, FR42, FR47\n170\t\n171\t### Epic 9: Workflow Configuration & Patching\n172\tCustom workflows or patches at project/user level. Changes without touching source.\n173\t**FRs:** FR13-15\n174\t\n175\t---\n176\t\n177\t## Epic 1: Legacy Cleanup & Foundation\n178\t\n179\tDeveloper has a clean codebase — beads removed, legacy files deleted, workflow-state module as foundation.\n180\t\n181\t### Story 1.1: Delete Beads Integration\n182\t\n183\tAs a developer,\n184\tI want all beads imports and calls removed from the codebase,\n185\tSo that I can build new features without dead dependency chains.\n186\t\n187\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n188\t\n189\t**Given** the current codebase has beads.ts and beads-sync.ts with 12+ dependent files\n190\t**When** beads.ts, beads-sync.ts, and all beads imports are removed\n191\t**Then** `npm run build` succeeds with zero beads references\n192\t**And** the 12 dependent files compile without beads imports\n193\t**And** `npm run test:unit` passes\n194\t\n195\t### Story 1.2: Delete Ralph Loop & Legacy Verification\n196\t\n197\tAs a developer,\n198\tI want the Ralph bash loop, old hooks, and proof document system deleted,\n199\tSo that only the new architecture's code paths exist.\n200\t\n201\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n202\t\n203\t**Given** ralph/ directory, hooks/ directory, and legacy lib modules exist\n204\t**When** all legacy files are deleted and their imports removed\n205\t**Then** ralph/ directory no longer exists\n206\t**And** hooks/ directory no longer exists\n207\t**And** src/lib/ does not contain verify.ts, verify-parser.ts, verifier-session.ts, patch-engine.ts, retry-state.ts, or old state.ts\n208\t**And** src/templates/ does not contain showboat-template.ts, verify-prompt.ts, or ralph-prompt.ts\n209\t**And** src/commands/retry.ts is deleted\n210\t**And** `npm run build` succeeds\n211\t**And** zero shell scripts remain in the execution path\n212\t\n213\t### Story 1.3: Workflow State Module\n214\t\n215\tAs a developer,\n216\tI want a workflow-state module that persists execution state to YAML,\n217\tSo that the engine can resume from the last completed task after a crash.\n218\t\n219\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n220\t\n221\t**Given** no workflow-state.yaml exists\n222\t**When** `writeState()` is called after a task completion\n223\t**Then** `.codeharness/workflow-state.yaml` is created with workflow name, started timestamp, iteration, phase, tasks_completed array, evaluator_scores array, and circuit_breaker state\n224\t**And** `readState()` returns the persisted state\n225\t**And** state survives process exit and is readable on restart\n226\t**And** unit tests cover read, write, crash recovery, and corrupted file handling at 80%+ coverage\n227\t\n228\t---\n229\t\n230\t## Epic 2: Workflow Definition & Validation\n231\t\n232\tDeveloper can author workflow YAML, validate it, and init generates a default.\n233\t\n234\t### Story 2.1: Workflow YAML JSON Schema\n235\t\n236\tAs a developer,\n237\tI want a JSON schema defining valid workflow YAML structure,\n238\tSo that malformed workflows are rejected at parse time.\n239\t\n240\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n241\t\n242\t**Given** a workflow YAML file\n243\t**When** validated against the JSON schema\n244\t**Then** valid workflows with tasks and flow pass validation\n245\t**And** missing required fields are rejected with specific errors\n246\t**And** invalid scope values are rejected\n247\t**And** loop: blocks with non-existent task references are rejected\n248\t**And** schema file exists at src/schemas/workflow.schema.json\n249\t\n250\t### Story 2.2: Workflow Parser Module\n251\t\n252\tAs a developer,\n253\tI want a workflow-parser module that loads, validates, and resolves workflow YAML,\n254\tSo that the engine receives a fully resolved config.\n255\t\n256\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n257\t\n258\t**Given** a workflow YAML file path\n259\t**When** `parseWorkflow()` is called\n260\t**Then** YAML is parsed and validated against the JSON schema\n261\t**And** invalid YAML returns a specific parse error\n262\t**And** parsing completes in <500ms\n263\t**And** returned object contains resolved tasks and flow with typed interfaces\n264\t**And** unit tests at 80%+ coverage\n265\t\n266\t### Story 2.3: Default Embedded Workflow\n267\t\n268\tAs a developer,\n269\tI want a default workflow YAML shipped with codeharness,\n270\tSo that `codeharness run` works without custom configuration.\n271\t\n272\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n273\t\n274\t**Given** codeharness is installed\n275\t**When** the default workflow is loaded from templates/workflows/default.yaml\n276\t**Then** it defines implement, verify, and retry tasks with correct properties\n277\t**And** flow is: implement → verify → loop: [retry, verify]\n278\t**And** it validates against the JSON schema\n279\t\n280\t### Story 2.4: Init Command — Workflow Generation\n281\t\n282\tAs a developer,\n283\tI want `codeharness init` to generate a default workflow in my project,\n284\tSo that I can start using codeharness without manual setup.\n285\t\n286\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n287\t\n288\t**Given** a project without .codeharness/workflows/\n289\t**When** `codeharness init` runs\n290\t**Then** `.codeharness/workflows/default.yaml` is created from embedded template\n291\t**And** existing stack detection still works\n292\t**And** `--force` overwrites existing workflow files\n293\t\n294\t### Story 2.5: Validate Command\n295\t\n296\tAs a developer,\n297\tI want `codeharness validate` to check YAML files against schemas,\n298\tSo that I catch configuration errors before running.\n299\t\n300\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n301\t\n302\t**Given** workflow and agent YAML files in the project\n303\t**When** `codeharness validate` runs\n304\t**Then** all YAML files are validated against their schemas\n305\t**And** errors report file path, line context, and specific violation\n306\t**And** exit code 0 on success, 1 on failure\n307\t\n308\t---\n309\t\n310\t## Epic 3: Agent Configuration System\n311\t\n312\t9 embedded agents, custom agents, patching, config resolution chain.\n313\t\n314\t### Story 3.1: Agent Config JSON Schema\n315\t\n316\tAs a developer,\n317\tI want a JSON schema defining valid agent configuration,\n318\tSo that malformed agent configs are caught before dispatch.\n319\t\n320\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n321\t\n322\t**Given** an agent YAML file\n323\t**When** validated against the schema\n324\t**Then** valid configs with name, role, persona, and optional personality.traits pass\n325\t**And** missing required fields are rejected\n326\t**And** traits outside 0-1 range are rejected\n327\t**And** schema file exists at src/schemas/agent.schema.json\n328\t\n329\t### Story 3.2: Embedded Agent Templates\n330\t\n331\tAs a developer,\n332\tI want 9 agent YAML files shipped with codeharness,\n333\tSo that the default workflow has agents to dispatch.\n334\t\n335\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n336\t\n337\t**Given** codeharness is installed\n338\t**When** embedded agents are loaded from templates/agents/\n339\t**Then** 9 agents exist: dev, qa, architect, pm, sm, analyst, ux-designer, tech-writer, evaluator\n340\t**And** each has name, role, persona fields from BMAD definitions\n341\t**And** evaluator has anti-leniency principles and disallowedTools\n342\t**And** all 9 validate against the agent JSON schema\n343\t**And** BMAD agent configs are never modified\n344\t\n345\t### Story 3.3: Agent Resolver Module\n346\t\n347\tAs a developer,\n348\tI want an agent-resolver that resolves configs through the patch chain,\n349\tSo that customizations overlay cleanly on embedded defaults.\n350\t\n351\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n352\t\n353\t**Given** an embedded agent and optional user/project patches\n354\t**When** `resolveAgent(\"dev\")` is called\n355\t**Then** embedded config is loaded, user patch merged if exists, project patch merged on top\n356\t**And** resolved config is compiled into a Claude Code inline subagent definition\n357\t**And** resolution completes in <200ms\n358\t**And** missing patches silently skipped, malformed patches fail loud\n359\t**And** unit tests at 80%+ coverage\n360\t\n361\t---\n362\t\n363\t## Epic 4: Agent Dispatch & Session Management\n364\t\n365\tEngine spawns Claude Code sessions via Agent SDK with session boundaries, trace IDs, source isolation.\n366\t\n367\t### Story 4.1: Agent Dispatch Module — SDK Integration\n368\t\n369\tAs a developer,\n370\tI want an agent-dispatch module that spawns sessions via the Agent SDK,\n371\tSo that agent execution is programmatic and reliable.\n372\t\n373\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n374\t\n375\t**Given** a compiled subagent definition and a prompt\n376\t**When** `dispatchAgent()` is called\n377\t**Then** Agent SDK `query()` is invoked with bare: true\n378\t**And** function returns when session completes\n379\t**And** spawn completes in <5s excluding model response\n380\t**And** no child_process.spawn used for Claude CLI\n381\t**And** API limit, network, and binary-not-found errors handled gracefully\n382\t\n383\t### Story 4.2: Session Boundary Management\n384\t\n385\tAs a developer,\n386\tI want session boundaries configurable per task,\n387\tSo that context resets and continuity are controlled.\n388\t\n389\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n390\t\n391\t**Given** a task with session: fresh\n392\t**When** dispatched\n393\t**Then** a new SDK query is created with no resume/continue\n394\t**And** given session: continue, previous session ID is passed via resume\n395\t**And** session IDs tracked in workflow-state\n396\t\n397\t### Story 4.3: Trace ID Generation & Injection\n398\t\n399\tAs a developer,\n400\tI want trace IDs generated per iteration and injected into prompts,\n401\tSo that agent activity correlates to observability data.\n402\t\n403\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n404\t\n405\t**Given** an iteration starting\n406\t**When** a trace ID is generated\n407\t**Then** format is `ch-{runId}-{iteration}-{taskName}`\n408\t**And** injected into agent's system prompt via appendSystemPrompt\n409\t**And** recorded in workflow-state.yaml\n410\t\n411\t### Story 4.4: Source Isolation Enforcement\n412\t\n413\tAs a developer,\n414\tI want source_access: false enforced via source-free workspace,\n415\tSo that the evaluator cannot access implementation code.\n416\t\n417\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n418\t\n419\t**Given** a task with source_access: false\n420\t**When** the agent is dispatched\n421\t**Then** temp directory created with only story files\n422\t**And** SDK cwd set to temp directory\n423\t**And** disallowedTools: [Edit, Write] set on subagent\n424\t**And** src/ not present in workspace\n425\t\n426\t---\n427\t\n428\t## Epic 5: Workflow Execution Engine\n429\t\n430\t`codeharness run` executes workflows — per-story, per-run, loop blocks, finding injection, reads stories and issues.\n431\t\n432\t### Story 5.1: Flow Execution — Sequential Steps\n433\t\n434\tAs a developer,\n435\tI want the engine to execute flow steps sequentially,\n436\tSo that tasks run in defined order.\n437\t\n438\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n439\t\n440\t**Given** a resolved workflow with flow: [implement, verify]\n441\t**When** `codeharness run` executes\n442\t**Then** per-story tasks run first (one per story/issue)\n443\t**And** per-run tasks run once after\n444\t**And** workflow-state updated after each task\n445\t**And** engine reads both sprint-status.yaml and issues.yaml\n446\t\n447\t### Story 5.2: Flow Execution — Loop Blocks\n448\t\n449\tAs a developer,\n450\tI want loop: blocks to repeat until pass or circuit breaker,\n451\tSo that retry cycles are automatic.\n452\t\n453\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n454\t\n455\t**Given** flow with loop: [retry, verify]\n456\t**When** verify produces non-passing verdict\n457\t**Then** retry runs for failed stories only with findings injected\n458\t**And** verify re-runs entire artifact from scratch\n459\t**And** loop repeats until all pass or max iterations\n460\t**And** each iteration recorded in workflow-state\n461\t\n462\t### Story 5.3: Crash Recovery & Resume\n463\t\n464\tAs a developer,\n465\tI want the engine to resume from last completed task after crash,\n466\tSo that long-running executions don't lose progress.\n467\t\n468\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n469\t\n470\t**Given** workflow-state shows tasks completed up to a checkpoint\n471\t**When** `codeharness run` or `--resume` starts\n472\t**Then** engine skips completed tasks, resumes from next\n473\t**And** no task executed twice\n474\t**And** 4+ hour executions don't degrade or leak\n475\t\n476\t### Story 5.4: Run & Status Commands\n477\t\n478\tAs a developer,\n479\tI want `codeharness run` and `codeharness status` to work,\n480\tSo that I can execute workflows and monitor progress.\n481\t\n482\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n483\t\n484\t**Given** a project with resolved workflow and sprint-status.yaml\n485\t**When** `codeharness run` executes\n486\t**Then** workflow engine is invoked\n487\t**And** `codeharness status` shows iteration, stories, scores, circuit breaker, elapsed time\n488\t**And** status returns in <1s\n489\t\n490\t---\n491\t\n492\t## Epic 6: Blind Evaluator & Verification\n493\t\n494\tBlind evaluator exercises artifact, produces JSON verdict, engine handles retry loop.\n495\t\n496\t### Story 6.1: Evaluator Module — Workspace & Spawn\n497\t\n498\tAs a developer,\n499\tI want an evaluator module that sets up source-free workspace and spawns the evaluator,\n500\tSo that verification is truly blind.\n501\t\n502\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n503\t\n504\t**Given** all stories are implemented\n505\t**When** evaluator task runs\n506\t**Then** temp workspace created with AC files and Docker access, no source\n507\t**And** evaluator spawned via agent-dispatch with bare: true, source_access: false\n508\t**And** Docker lifecycle managed by engine\n509\t**And** if Docker not running, verdict is all UNKNOWN with finding\n510\t**And** timeout produces scored UNKNOWN, not fatal error\n511\t\n512\t### Story 6.2: Evaluator Verdict JSON Schema & Parsing\n513\t\n514\tAs a developer,\n515\tI want the evaluator to produce structured JSON validated by schema,\n516\tSo that every AC has status and evidence.\n517\t\n518\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n519\t\n520\t**Given** evaluator completes its session\n521\t**When** output is parsed\n522\t**Then** conforms to verdict schema: verdict, score, findings with per-AC status and evidence\n523\t**And** invalid JSON triggers one retry, then all UNKNOWN\n524\t**And** schema at src/schemas/verdict.schema.json\n525\t**And** every PASS has non-empty evidence.commands_run\n526\t\n527\t### Story 6.3: Evaluator Prompt Template\n528\t\n529\tAs a developer,\n530\tI want the evaluator agent YAML to include anti-leniency instructions,\n531\tSo that the evaluator requires evidence for every verdict.\n532\t\n533\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n534\t\n535\t**Given** evaluator loaded from templates/agents/evaluator.yaml\n536\t**When** compiled to subagent definition\n537\t**Then** prompt instructs: read ACs, independently test, evidence for every PASS, UNKNOWN if can't verify, never benefit of the doubt\n538\t**And** evaluator can query observability endpoints\n539\t\n540\t---\n541\t\n542\t## Epic 7: Circuit Breaker & Progress Detection\n543\t\n544\tScore-based stagnation detection, halt, reporting, resume.\n545\t\n546\t### Story 7.1: Score-Based Circuit Breaker Module\n547\t\n548\tAs a developer,\n549\tI want a circuit breaker that detects evaluator score stagnation,\n550\tSo that the engine halts instead of burning tokens.\n551\t\n552\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n553\t\n554\t**Given** evaluator scores across iterations\n555\t**When** `evaluateProgress()` called after each verify\n556\t**Then** stagnation detected when scores don't improve\n557\t**And** returns halt with remaining failures and score history\n558\t**And** evaluation in <100ms\n559\t**And** unit tests at 80%+ coverage\n560\t\n561\t### Story 7.2: Resume After Circuit Breaker\n562\t\n563\tAs a developer,\n564\tI want to resume after circuit breaker halts,\n565\tSo that I can apply manual fixes and re-run.\n566\t\n567\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n568\t\n569\t**Given** circuit breaker has halted\n570\t**When** `codeharness run --resume` executes\n571\t**Then** engine reads state, resets circuit breaker for current iteration\n572\t**And** resumes from verify step\n573\t**And** previous findings available in state\n574\t\n575\t---\n576\t\n577\t## Epic 8: Issue Tracking & Retro Integration\n578\t\n579\t`codeharness issue` CLI, retro auto-import, issues execute alongside stories.\n580\t\n581\t### Story 8.1: Issue Tracker Module & CLI\n582\t\n583\tAs a developer,\n584\tI want to create, list, and manage issues via `codeharness issue`,\n585\tSo that bugs and tech debt have a path to implementation.\n586\t\n587\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n588\t\n589\t**Given** no issues.yaml exists\n590\t**When** `codeharness issue create \"Fix Docker timeout\" --priority high --source retro-sprint-1` runs\n591\t**Then** issues.yaml created with auto-generated id, title, source, priority, status: backlog\n592\t**And** `codeharness issue list` shows all issues\n593\t**And** `codeharness issue close issue-001` updates status to done\n594\t**And** same status values as sprint-status.yaml\n595\t\n596\t### Story 8.2: Retro Finding Auto-Import\n597\t\n598\tAs a developer,\n599\tI want retro findings tagged as actionable to appear in issues.yaml,\n600\tSo that action items don't rot in markdown.\n601\t\n602\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n603\t\n604\t**Given** a retrospective file with actionable findings\n605\t**When** `codeharness retro-import` runs\n606\t**Then** actionable findings added to issues.yaml with retro source\n607\t**And** duplicate detection prevents re-importing\n608\t**And** non-actionable findings ignored\n609\t\n610\t---\n611\t\n612\t## Epic 9: Workflow Configuration & Patching\n613\t\n614\tCustom workflows or patches at project/user level.\n615\t\n616\t### Story 9.1: Workflow Patch Resolution\n617\t\n618\tAs a developer,\n619\tI want to patch the default workflow via a patch file,\n620\tSo that I can customize execution without replacing the entire workflow.\n621\t\n622\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n623\t\n624\t**Given** embedded default workflow and project-level patch with extends: embedded://default\n625\t**When** workflow parser resolves\n626\t**Then** structured overrides merged onto embedded base\n627\t**And** replace overrides replace entire sections\n628\t**And** missing patches silently skipped\n629\t**And** malformed patches fail loud\n630\t**And** user-level patches applied before project-level\n631\t\n632\t### Story 9.2: Custom Workflow Creation\n633\t\n634\tAs a developer,\n635\tI want to create a custom workflow YAML in my project,\n636\tSo that I can define non-standard execution flows.\n637\t\n638\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n639\t\n640\t**Given** custom workflow at .codeharness/workflows/my-workflow.yaml\n641\t**When** `codeharness run --workflow my-workflow` executes\n642\t**Then** custom workflow loaded, validated, and executed\n643\t**And** must pass JSON schema validation\n644\t**And** agent references resolve through same config chain\n645\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01Tuyo7ARsiRwTfcugHgbJ4e","session_id":"06dc1e0b-83a0-4950-9e66-ec9396bae461","uuid":"e8ccef6b-7306-48d0-b5d6-8cec94eefc0f","timestamp":"2026-04-02T11:25:58.087Z"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01133iuEFUXkXk7Z4iJCxF4N","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tstepsCompleted: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8]\n3\tlastStep: 8\n4\tstatus: 'complete'\n5\tcompletedAt: '2026-04-02'\n6\tinputDocuments:\n7\t  - prd-evaluator-redesign.md\n8\t  - research/domain-harness-design-long-running-agents-research-2026-04-01.md\n9\t  - research/technical-ai-agent-verification-testing-research-2026-03-16.md\n10\t  - research/technical-workflow-engine-implementation-research-2026-04-02.md\n11\t  - architecture.md (v1 architecture, brownfield context)\n12\tworkflowType: 'architecture'\n13\tproject_name: 'codeharness'\n14\tuser_name: 'BMad'\n15\tdate: '2026-04-02'\n16\t---\n17\t\n18\t# Architecture Decision Document\n19\t\n20\t_This document builds collaboratively through step-by-step discovery. Sections are appended as we work through each architectural decision together._\n21\t\n22\t## Project Context Analysis\n23\t\n24\t### Requirements Overview\n25\t\n26\t**Functional Requirements:** 43 FRs across 10 capability areas — Workflow Definition (6), Agent Configuration (6), Workflow Configuration (3), Workflow Execution (8), Adversarial Verification (5), Feedback Loop (3), Circuit Breaker (4), Observability (2), CLI Commands (4), Legacy Removal (2).\n27\t\n28\t**Non-Functional Requirements:** 18 NFRs across Performance (5), Reliability (5), Integration (4), Code Quality (4). Architecture-critical NFRs: crash recovery via state persistence (NFR6-8), programmatic agent dispatch only (NFR11), optional observability (NFR14).\n29\t\n30\t**Scale & Complexity:**\n31\t- Primary domain: Developer tooling (CLI + plugin)\n32\t- Complexity level: High\n33\t- Estimated architectural components: ~10\n34\t- Cross-cutting concerns: config resolution chain, trace ID propagation, crash recovery, evaluator isolation\n35\t\n36\t### Technical Constraints & Dependencies\n37\t\n38\t- Runtime: Node.js (TypeScript)\n39\t- Dependencies: `commander`, `yaml`, `@anthropic-ai/claude-agent-sdk`\n40\t- Execution substrate: Agent SDK `query()` — async generator, session management, JSON schema output\n41\t- State: Single `workflow-state.yaml` in repo (beads-level simplicity)\n42\t- Evaluator isolation: Separate workspace, no source code, Docker container for artifact\n43\t- Docker: Required for evaluator but graceful degradation if missing (Journey 5)\n44\t\n45\t### Cross-Cutting Concerns\n46\t\n47\t1. **Config resolution** — every agent/workflow dispatch resolves embedded → user → project patches\n48\t2. **Trace ID propagation** — generated per iteration, injected into agent prompts, correlates to observability\n49\t3. **Crash recovery** — state persisted after each task, engine resumes from last checkpoint\n50\t4. **Evaluator isolation** — separate workspace, `disallowedTools` enforcement, `source_access: false`\n51\t\n52\t## Starter Template Evaluation\n53\t\n54\t### Primary Technology Domain\n55\t\n56\tCLI developer tool — Node.js/TypeScript. Brownfield project with established toolchain.\n57\t\n58\t### Starter Options: Not Applicable (Brownfield)\n59\t\n60\tExisting project toolchain is retained:\n61\t\n62\t| Decision | Current (Keep) | Source |\n63\t|----------|---------------|--------|\n64\t| Language | TypeScript (strict) | Existing project |\n65\t| Build | tsup | Existing project |\n66\t| Test | vitest (unit) + BATS (integration) | Existing project |\n67\t| CLI | commander | Existing project |\n68\t| YAML | yaml package | Existing project |\n69\t| **New** | @anthropic-ai/claude-agent-sdk | Research — replaces bash spawn |\n70\t\n71\t**No starter template needed.** One new dependency added. Internals reworked.\n72\t\n73\t## Core Architectural Decisions\n74\t\n75\t### Decision Priority Analysis\n76\t\n77\t**Critical Decisions (Block Implementation):**\n78\t1. Module boundaries — what code goes where\n79\t2. Evaluator workspace isolation — how to enforce source-free verification\n80\t3. Evaluator verdict schema — the contract between evaluator and engine\n81\t\n82\t**Important Decisions (Shape Architecture):**\n83\t4. Embedded template storage — where agent/workflow YAML files live in the package\n84\t5. Config resolution caching — resolve once or every dispatch\n85\t\n86\t**Deferred Decisions (Post-MVP):**\n87\t- PersonaNexus trait compilation algorithm (Growth phase)\n88\t- Pluggable evaluator strategies interface (Growth phase)\n89\t- Workflow marketplace format/registry (Vision phase)\n90\t\n91\t### AD1: Module Boundaries\n92\t\n93\t| Module | Responsibility | Key FRs |\n94\t|--------|---------------|---------|\n95\t| `workflow-parser` | Parse YAML, validate against JSON schema, resolve patches (embedded→user→project) | FR1-6, FR13-15 |\n96\t| `agent-resolver` | Resolve agent config through patch chain, compile to SDK inline subagent definition | FR7-12 |\n97\t| `workflow-engine` | Execute flow steps, manage iterations, handle `loop:` blocks, inject evaluator findings into retries | FR16-18, FR29-31 |\n98\t| `agent-dispatch` | Call Agent SDK `query()`, manage sessions (fresh/continue), inject trace IDs | FR19-23 |\n99\t| `evaluator` | Blind evaluator workspace setup, spawn, JSON verdict parsing | FR24-28 |\n100\t| `circuit-breaker` | Score-based stagnation detection, score history tracking | FR32-35 |\n101\t| `workflow-state` | Read/write workflow-state.yaml, crash recovery (resume from last completed task) | NFR6-8 |\n102\t\n103\t**Rationale:** 7 modules, each 100-200 LOC. Feedback loop (FR29-30) is part of `workflow-engine` — it's loop logic, not a separate concern. CLI commands (`init`, `run`, `validate`, `status`) are thin wrappers calling these modules. Observability (FR36-37) is a cross-cutting concern handled by trace ID injection in `agent-dispatch`, not a separate module.\n104\t\n105\t### AD2: Evaluator Workspace Isolation\n106\t\n107\t**Decision:** Temp directory with only story files + Docker access.\n108\t\n109\t```\n110\t/tmp/codeharness-verify-{runId}/\n111\t  story-files/     # copied ACs from sprint\n112\t  verdict/         # evaluator writes JSON verdict here\n113\t```\n114\t\n115\tEngine copies story files to temp dir, spawns evaluator with `cwd` set to this directory. Agent SDK options enforce isolation:\n116\t- `bare: true` — no plugins, hooks, MCP, memory\n117\t- `disallowedTools: [\"Edit\", \"Write\"]` — read-only + execute only\n118\t- `cwd: /tmp/codeharness-verify-{runId}` — no source code present\n119\t\n120\t**Rationale:** Simplest approach. Source isn't there because we never put it there. No git worktree complexity, no Docker-in-Docker. The Agent SDK's `cwd` + `disallowedTools` provide sufficient isolation.\n121\t\n122\t### AD3: Embedded Template Storage\n123\t\n124\t**Decision:** `templates/` directory in the npm package.\n125\t\n126\t```\n127\ttemplates/\n128\t  agents/\n129\t    dev.yaml\n130\t    qa.yaml\n131\t    architect.yaml\n132\t    pm.yaml\n133\t    sm.yaml\n134\t    analyst.yaml\n135\t    ux-designer.yaml\n136\t    tech-writer.yaml\n137\t    evaluator.yaml\n138\t  workflows/\n139\t    default.yaml\n140\t```\n141\t\n142\tIncluded via `package.json` `files` array. Readable, editable for debugging, consistent with existing pattern (`templates/Dockerfile.verify`).\n143\t\n144\t**Rationale:** Files over compiled strings. Easier to inspect, diff, and debug. The `codeharness init` command copies the default workflow to the project; embedded agents are resolved at runtime from the package location.\n145\t\n146\t### AD4: Config Resolution Caching\n147\t\n148\t**Decision:** Resolve all configs once at engine startup, cache in memory.\n149\t\n150\tOn `codeharness run`:\n151\t1. Resolve workflow: load embedded → apply user patch → apply project patch → cache\n152\t2. Resolve all referenced agents: same resolution chain → cache\n153\t3. Run engine with cached configs — no file I/O during execution\n154\t\n155\t**Rationale:** Config files don't change during a run. Caching guarantees NFR2 (<200ms resolution) and eliminates repeated file system reads during long-running execution.\n156\t\n157\t### AD5: Evaluator Verdict Schema\n158\t\n159\t**Decision:** Structured JSON enforced by Agent SDK `jsonSchema` option.\n160\t\n161\t```typescript\n162\tinterface EvaluatorVerdict {\n163\t  verdict: 'pass' | 'fail';\n164\t  score: {\n165\t    passed: number;\n166\t    failed: number;\n167\t    unknown: number;\n168\t    total: number;\n169\t  };\n170\t  findings: Array<{\n171\t    ac: number;\n172\t    description: string;\n173\t    status: 'pass' | 'fail' | 'unknown';\n174\t    evidence: {\n175\t      commands_run: string[];\n176\t      output_observed: string;\n177\t      reasoning: string;\n178\t    };\n179\t  }>;\n180\t  evaluator_trace_id: string;\n181\t  duration_seconds: number;\n182\t}\n183\t```\n184\t\n185\t**Rationale:** Replaces the 175-line proof document regex parser entirely. The Agent SDK validates the output against this schema — if the evaluator doesn't produce valid JSON, the SDK rejects it. Every AC verdict requires evidence (commands + output), enforcing the anti-leniency principle structurally.\n186\t\n187\t### Decision Impact Analysis\n188\t\n189\t**Implementation Sequence:**\n190\t1. `workflow-state` — foundation for crash recovery, needed by everything\n191\t2. `workflow-parser` — parse YAML + resolve patches, needed before execution\n192\t3. `agent-resolver` — resolve agent configs, needed before dispatch\n193\t4. `agent-dispatch` — SDK integration, needed before engine can run\n194\t5. `workflow-engine` — orchestrates everything above\n195\t6. `evaluator` — depends on dispatch + state\n196\t7. `circuit-breaker` — depends on evaluator verdicts\n197\t\n198\t**Cross-Component Dependencies:**\n199\t- `workflow-engine` depends on all other modules\n200\t- `evaluator` depends on `agent-dispatch` (for SDK spawn) and `workflow-state` (for verdict recording)\n201\t- `circuit-breaker` depends on `workflow-state` (reads score history)\n202\t- `agent-dispatch` depends on `agent-resolver` (for compiled subagent definitions)\n203\t\n204\t## Implementation Patterns & Consistency Rules\n205\t\n206\t### Naming Patterns\n207\t\n208\t**File naming:** `kebab-case.ts` for all source files. Already established (`workflow-parser.ts`, `agent-dispatch.ts`).\n209\t\n210\t**Export naming:** `camelCase` for functions, `PascalCase` for types/interfaces, `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE` for constants.\n211\t\n212\t**YAML keys:** `snake_case` for all workflow and agent config keys (`source_access`, `max_budget_usd`).\n213\t\n214\t**Patch files:** Named `{base-name}.patch.yaml`. Always. Not `.override.yaml` or `.custom.yaml`.\n215\t\n216\t### Structure Patterns\n217\t\n218\tEach module in `src/lib/` is one file with co-located test:\n219\t```\n220\tsrc/lib/workflow-parser.ts\n221\tsrc/lib/__tests__/workflow-parser.test.ts\n222\t```\n223\t\n224\tEmbedded templates: `templates/agents/`, `templates/workflows/`.\n225\tUser-level: `~/.codeharness/agents/`, `~/.codeharness/workflows/`.\n226\tProject-level: `.codeharness/agents/`, `.codeharness/workflows/`.\n227\tNo alternative locations.\n228\t\n229\t### Format Patterns\n230\t\n231\t**Evaluator verdict:** JSON schema enforced (AD5). No alternative formats. Every AC requires `status`, `evidence.commands_run`, `evidence.output_observed`.\n232\t\n233\t**Workflow state:** YAML in `.codeharness/workflow-state.yaml`. No JSON, no SQLite, no binary.\n234\t\n235\t**Resolved configs:** In-memory only. Never written to disk.\n236\t\n237\t### Error Handling Patterns\n238\t\n239\t| Failure | Response |\n240\t|---------|----------|\n241\t| API limit | Record in state, wait and retry |\n242\t| Network failure | Record in state, retry with backoff |\n243\t| Agent timeout | Score as UNKNOWN, continue |\n244\t| Binary not found | Fatal error, halt engine |\n245\t| Missing embedded agent | Fatal error at startup |\n246\t| Malformed patch YAML | Fatal error with parse error |\n247\t| Missing user/project patch | Silently skip |\n248\t| Evaluator timeout | All UNKNOWN, counts as scored iteration |\n249\t| Invalid evaluator JSON | Retry once, then all UNKNOWN |\n250\t| Docker not running | All UNKNOWN with \"Docker not available\" finding |\n251\t\n252\t### Process Patterns\n253\t\n254\t**State writes:** After EVERY task completion. Never batch. Never defer. Crash recovery guarantee.\n255\t\n256\t**Trace ID format:** `ch-{runId}-{iteration}-{taskName}` — deterministic, greppable. Example: `ch-abc123-3-verify`.\n257\t\n258\t**Session boundary enforcement:** `session: fresh` = new Agent SDK query with no resume/continue. No session reuse optimization across tasks.\n259\t\n260\t### Enforcement Guidelines\n261\t\n262\t**All agents implementing codeharness v2 MUST:**\n263\t- Run `vitest run` before marking any module complete — 80%+ coverage\n264\t- Use Agent SDK `query()` for all agent dispatch — never `execFileSync`\n265\t- Write workflow-state.yaml after every task — never hold state only in memory\n266\t- Use `bare: true` for all programmatic agent spawns\n267\t\n268\t**Anti-Patterns:**\n269\t- Caching evaluator verdicts across iterations (each is full re-verification)\n270\t- Writing resolved configs to disk (memory-only)\n271\t- Using `child_process.spawn` for Claude CLI\n272\t- Adding shell scripts to the execution path\n273\t\n274\t## Project Structure & Boundaries\n275\t\n276\t### Complete Project Directory Structure\n277\t\n278\t```\n279\tcodeharness/\n280\t├── package.json\n281\t├── tsconfig.json\n282\t├── tsup.config.ts\n283\t├── vitest.config.ts\n284\t├── .github/workflows/release.yml\n285\t│\n286\t├── src/\n287\t│   ├── index.ts                           # CLI entry point (commander)\n288\t│   │\n289\t│   ├── commands/                           # CLI command handlers\n290\t│   │   ├── init.ts                        # REWORK — add workflow generation, strip beads\n291\t│   │   ├── run.ts                         # REWORK — use workflow-engine instead of Ralph\n292\t│   │   ├── validate.ts                    # NEW — schema validation command\n293\t│   │   ├── status.ts                      # REWORK — show workflow-state, strip beads\n294\t│   │   ├── verify.ts                      # REWORK — becomes evaluator trigger only\n295\t│   │   ├── coverage.ts                    # KEEP as-is\n296\t│   │   ├── doc-health.ts                  # KEEP as-is\n297\t│   │   ├── stack.ts                       # KEEP as-is\n298\t│   │   ├── query.ts                       # KEEP as-is (observability queries)\n299\t│   │   ├── bridge.ts                      # REWORK — strip beads, keep BMAD bridge\n300\t│   │   ├── sync.ts                        # REWORK — strip beads sync\n301\t│   │   ├── onboard.ts                     # REWORK — strip beads calls\n302\t│   │   ├── teardown.ts                    # REWORK — update for new file layout\n303\t│   │   ├── state.ts                       # REWORK — point at workflow-state.yaml\n304\t│   │   ├── retro-import.ts               # REWORK — strip beads imports\n305\t│   │   ├── github-import.ts              # REWORK — strip beads imports\n306\t│   │   ├── verify-env.ts                  # REWORK — evolve into evaluator setup\n307\t│   │   └── __tests__/\n308\t│   │\n309\t│   ├── lib/                               # Core modules\n310\t│   │   │\n311\t│   │   │  # ── NEW MODULES (v2 architecture) ──\n312\t│   │   ├── workflow-parser.ts             # YAML parse, schema validate, patch resolution\n313\t│   │   ├── agent-resolver.ts             # Agent config resolution, SDK compilation\n314\t│   │   ├── workflow-engine.ts            # Flow execution, loops, finding injection\n315\t│   │   ├── agent-dispatch.ts             # Agent SDK query(), sessions, trace IDs\n316\t│   │   ├── evaluator.ts                  # Blind evaluator workspace + spawn + verdict parsing\n317\t│   │   ├── circuit-breaker.ts            # Score-based stagnation detection (TS rewrite)\n318\t│   │   ├── workflow-state.ts             # State persistence, crash recovery (replaces state.ts)\n319\t│   │   │\n320\t│   │   │  # ── KEPT MODULES (existing, no changes) ──\n321\t│   │   ├── output.ts                      # Console output utilities\n322\t│   │   ├── stack-detect.ts               # Stack detection for init\n323\t│   │   ├── stack-path.ts                 # Docker compose and OTLP config paths\n324\t│   │   ├── docker.ts                      # Docker Compose lifecycle management\n325\t│   │   ├── otlp.ts                        # OpenTelemetry instrumentation setup\n326\t│   │   ├── scanner.ts                     # Codebase scanning\n327\t│   │   ├── scan-cache.ts                 # Scan result persistence\n328\t│   │   ├── coverage.ts                    # Coverage tool detection\n329\t│   │   ├── doc-health.ts                 # Documentation freshness checking\n330\t│   │   ├── templates.ts                   # File rendering and generation\n331\t│   │   ├── github.ts                      # GitHub CLI wrapper\n332\t│   │   ├── retro-parser.ts              # Retrospective markdown parsing\n333\t│   │   │\n334\t│   │   │  # ── REWORK MODULES (strip beads, keep core logic) ──\n335\t│   │   ├── bmad.ts                        # REWORK — strip beads gap-IDs, keep BMAD install/patch\n336\t│   │   ├── epic-generator.ts             # REWORK — strip beads gap-IDs, keep epic generation\n337\t│   │   ├── onboard-checks.ts            # REWORK — strip beads calls, keep preconditions\n338\t│   │   ├── deps.ts                        # REWORK — remove showboat/beads deps\n339\t│   │   ├── verify-env.ts                 # REWORK — evolve into evaluator workspace setup\n340\t│   │   │\n341\t│   │   └── __tests__/                     # Co-located unit tests (update with source)\n342\t│   │\n343\t│   ├── templates/                         # Code-generated templates\n344\t│   │   ├── readme.ts                      # KEEP — README generator\n345\t│   │   ├── docker-compose.ts             # KEEP — observability stack template\n346\t│   │   ├── otel-config.ts               # KEEP — OpenTelemetry config\n347\t│   │   ├── bmad-patches.ts              # KEEP — BMAD workflow patch templates\n348\t│   │   └── __tests__/\n349\t│   │\n350\t│   └── schemas/                           # JSON schemas (NEW)\n351\t│       ├── workflow.schema.json\n352\t│       ├── agent.schema.json\n353\t│       └── verdict.schema.json\n354\t│\n355\t├── templates/                             # Embedded defaults (shipped in npm)\n356\t│   ├── agents/                            # 9 agent YAMLs (8 BMAD + evaluator)\n357\t│   │   ├── dev.yaml\n358\t│   │   ├── qa.yaml\n359\t│   │   ├── architect.yaml\n360\t│   │   ├── pm.yaml\n361\t│   │   ├── sm.yaml\n362\t│   │   ├── analyst.yaml\n363\t│   │   ├── ux-designer.yaml\n364\t│   │   ├── tech-writer.yaml\n365\t│   │   └── evaluator.yaml\n366\t│   └── workflows/\n367\t│       └── default.yaml                   # Default sprint execution workflow\n368\t│\n369\t├── tests/                                 # BATS integration tests (rework for v2)\n370\t│\n371\t├── .claude-plugin/\n372\t│   └── plugin.json                        # REWORK — update hooks, remove old references\n373\t│\n374\t├── skills/                                # REWORK — update for v2 architecture\n375\t│   ├── harness-run/\n376\t│   ├── harness-status/\n377\t│   └── harness-init/\n378\t│\n379\t└── dist/                                  # Build output (tsup)\n380\t```\n381\t\n382\t### Complete File Migration Plan\n383\t\n384\t#### DELETE (40+ files)\n385\t\n386\t**Entire directories:**\n387\t- `ralph/` — 23 files (ralph.sh, drivers/, lib/, logs/, state files)\n388\t- `hooks/` — 5 files (4 bash hooks + hooks.json)\n389\t\n390\t**From `src/lib/` (7 files):**\n391\t- `beads.ts` — Beads CLI wrapper (entire beads integration removed)\n392\t- `beads-sync.ts` — Beads ↔ story sync\n393\t- `verify.ts` — 175-line proof parser (replaced by evaluator.ts)\n394\t- `verify-parser.ts` — Story AC parser (simplified into evaluator)\n395\t- `verifier-session.ts` — Black-box verifier subprocess (evolved into evaluator.ts)\n396\t- `patch-engine.ts` — Marker-based patching (replaced by workflow-parser.ts)\n397\t- `retry-state.ts` — Retry counter persistence (merged into workflow-state.ts)\n398\t- `state.ts` — Old session flags state (replaced by workflow-state.ts)\n399\t\n400\t**From `src/templates/` (3 files):**\n401\t- `showboat-template.ts` — Proof document format (replaced by JSON verdict)\n402\t- `verify-prompt.ts` — Black-box verifier prompt (replaced by evaluator agent YAML)\n403\t- `ralph-prompt.ts` — Ralph loop prompt (replaced by workflow engine)\n404\t\n405\t**From `src/commands/` (1 file):**\n406\t- `retry.ts` — Retry command (merged into workflow-state)\n407\t\n408\t**All corresponding test files for deleted sources.**\n409\t\n410\t#### REWORK — Beads Cleanup (12 files)\n411\t\n412\tThese files import beads functions that must be surgically removed:\n413\t\n414\t| File | What to Remove | What to Keep |\n415\t|------|---------------|-------------|\n416\t| `src/lib/bmad.ts` | `appendGapId`, beads issue creation | BMAD install, workflow patching |\n417\t| `src/lib/epic-generator.ts` | `appendGapId`, beads calls | Epic generation from scan |\n418\t| `src/lib/onboard-checks.ts` | Beads precondition checks | Non-beads preconditions |\n419\t| `src/lib/deps.ts` | Showboat/beads dep installation | Claude, Docker dep checks |\n420\t| `src/lib/verify-env.ts` | Old verifier workspace logic | Evolve into evaluator workspace |\n421\t| `src/commands/bridge.ts` | `createIssue`, `listIssues` imports | BMAD story bridge logic |\n422\t| `src/commands/init.ts` | Beads init, hook installation | Stack detect, workflow generation |\n423\t| `src/commands/onboard.ts` | Beads calls from epic-generator | Scanning, epic generation |\n424\t| `src/commands/status.ts` | Beads status display | Workflow-state display |\n425\t| `src/commands/sync.ts` | Beads sync operations | Sprint-status sync |\n426\t| `src/commands/teardown.ts` | Old patch-engine calls | New file layout cleanup |\n427\t| `src/commands/verify.ts` | Self-verification, proof parsing | Evaluator trigger only |\n428\t\n429\t#### REWORK — Architecture Changes (5 files)\n430\t\n431\t| File | Change |\n432\t|------|--------|\n433\t| `src/commands/run.ts` | Replace Ralph spawn with workflow-engine call |\n434\t| `src/commands/state.ts` | Point at workflow-state.yaml instead of old state |\n435\t| `src/commands/retro-import.ts` | Strip beads imports |\n436\t| `src/commands/github-import.ts` | Strip beads imports |\n437\t| `.claude-plugin/plugin.json` | Remove old hook references, update version |\n438\t\n439\t#### REWORK — Skills (3 directories)\n440\t\n441\t| Skill | Change |\n442\t|-------|--------|\n443\t| `skills/harness-run/` | Update to reference workflow-engine |\n444\t| `skills/harness-status/` | Update to reference workflow-state |\n445\t| `skills/harness-init/` | Update for new init flow |\n446\t\n447\t#### NEW (20+ files)\n448\t\n449\t- 7 core modules in `src/lib/` (workflow-parser, agent-resolver, workflow-engine, agent-dispatch, evaluator, circuit-breaker, workflow-state)\n450\t- 3 JSON schemas in `src/schemas/`\n451\t- 9 agent YAMLs in `templates/agents/`\n452\t- 1 workflow YAML in `templates/workflows/`\n453\t- 1 new command (`src/commands/validate.ts`)\n454\t- Co-located tests for all new modules\n455\t\n456\t### FR → Module Mapping\n457\t\n458\t| FR Group | Module |\n459\t|----------|--------|\n460\t| FR1-6, FR13-15 (Workflow + Config) | workflow-parser |\n461\t| FR7-12 (Agent Config) | agent-resolver |\n462\t| FR16-18, FR29-31 (Execution + Feedback) | workflow-engine |\n463\t| FR19-23 (Dispatch) | agent-dispatch |\n464\t| FR24-28 (Verification) | evaluator |\n465\t| FR32-35 (Circuit Breaker) | circuit-breaker |\n466\t| FR36-37 (Observability) | agent-dispatch (trace IDs) |\n467\t| FR38-41 (CLI) | commands/*.ts |\n468\t\n469\t### Dependency Chain Breaks to Handle\n470\t\n471\t| Deleted Module | Dependents That Need Cleanup |\n472\t|---------------|------------------------------|\n473\t| `beads.ts` | bmad.ts, epic-generator.ts, onboard-checks.ts, bridge, github-import, init, onboard, retro-import, status, sync, verify |\n474\t| `beads-sync.ts` | sync.ts, verify.ts, run.ts |\n475\t| `verify-parser.ts` | verify.ts |\n476\t| `verifier-session.ts` | (no external dependents — self-contained) |\n477\t| `patch-engine.ts` | bmad.ts, teardown.ts |\n478\t| `retry-state.ts` | retry.ts (deleted), run.ts |\n479\t| `state.ts` | verify.ts, status.ts, state.ts command, init.ts |\n480\t| `ralph-prompt.ts` | run.ts |\n481\t| `showboat-template.ts` | verify.ts |\n482\t\n483\t### Integration Boundaries & Data Flow\n484\t\n485\t```\n486\tcodeharness run\n487\t  → workflow-parser: load + resolve workflow YAML\n488\t  → agent-resolver: resolve all referenced agents, cache\n489\t  → workflow-engine: execute flow steps\n490\t    → per-story tasks:\n491\t        agent-dispatch: SDK query() → agent works → returns\n492\t        workflow-state: write checkpoint\n493\t    → per-run tasks (verify):\n494\t        evaluator: setup workspace → agent-dispatch → parse verdict\n495\t        workflow-state: write checkpoint + scores\n496\t        circuit-breaker: evaluate stagnation\n497\t    → loop block: repeat with findings injected\n498\t  → workflow-state: write final status\n499\t```\n500\t\n501\t## Architecture Validation Results\n502\t\n503\t### Coherence Validation\n504\t\n505\t**Decision Compatibility:** All technology choices (Agent SDK + TypeScript + commander + yaml) are Node.js ecosystem, no conflicts. Agent SDK async generator + sequential engine execution are compatible. JSON schema validation consistent across workflow, agent, and verdict schemas.\n506\t\n507\t**Pattern Consistency:** kebab-case files + camelCase exports matches existing codebase. snake_case YAML keys is standard cross-language convention. Write-after-task state pattern aligns with crash recovery requirement.\n508\t\n509\t**Structure Alignment:** 7 modules in `src/lib/` with co-located tests matches existing structure. Templates in `templates/` matches existing distribution. `.codeharness/` for project config is clean separation from `.claude/`.\n510\t\n511\t**No contradictions found.**\n512\t\n513\t### Requirements Coverage\n514\t\n515\t**43 FRs:** All mapped to specific modules. No FR unaddressed.\n516\t\n517\t**18 NFRs:** All addressed — performance by caching, reliability by state persistence, integration by Agent SDK, code quality by project structure.\n518\t\n519\t**Minor gap:** Verdict schema needs `infrastructure_available: boolean` for graceful degradation when Docker is unavailable (Journey 5). Resolution: add the field.\n520\t\n521\t### Implementation Readiness\n522\t\n523\t- 5 architectural decisions documented with rationale\n524\t- Implementation sequence defined (state → parser → resolver → dispatch → engine → evaluator → circuit-breaker)\n525\t- Full directory tree with every file specified\n526\t- Legacy deletion targets listed explicitly\n527\t- Error handling patterns cover all failure modes\n528\t- Enforcement guidelines and anti-patterns documented\n529\t\n530\t### Architecture Completeness Checklist\n531\t\n532\t- [x] Project context analyzed\n533\t- [x] Technical constraints identified\n534\t- [x] Cross-cutting concerns mapped (config resolution, trace IDs, crash recovery, evaluator isolation)\n535\t- [x] 5 core architectural decisions documented\n536\t- [x] Technology stack specified\n537\t- [x] Naming, structure, format, error, and process patterns defined\n538\t- [x] Complete directory structure with every file classified (DELETE/REWORK/KEEP/NEW)\n539\t- [x] FR→module mapping complete\n540\t- [x] Integration boundaries and data flow documented\n541\t- [x] Beads dependency chain mapped — 12 files need surgical cleanup\n542\t- [x] All 17 existing commands accounted for (not just the 4 new/reworked ones)\n543\t- [x] All 14 kept lib modules listed with their role in v2\n544\t- [x] All 4 kept templates listed\n545\t- [x] Skills and plugin.json rework noted\n546\t- [x] Dependency chain breaks documented with specific cleanup actions\n547\t\n548\t### Architecture Readiness Assessment\n549\t\n550\t**Status:** READY FOR IMPLEMENTATION\n551\t**Confidence:** High\n552\t\n553\t**Migration scope (revised):**\n554\t- ~40 files deleted (ralph/, hooks/, 8 lib modules, 3 templates, 1 command + tests)\n555\t- ~17 files reworked (12 beads cleanup, 5 architecture changes)\n556\t- ~14 lib files kept as-is\n557\t- ~20 new files (7 modules, 3 schemas, 10 templates, tests)\n558\t\n559\t**Strengths:** Clean module boundaries, complete file migration plan, dependency chain breaks documented, official SDK replaces bash spawning, beads-level state simplicity, structural evaluator isolation.\n560\t\n561\t**Key risk:** Beads cleanup touches 12 files — must be done atomically to avoid broken imports. Recommended: delete beads.ts + beads-sync.ts first, then fix all compiler errors in one pass.\n562\t\n563\t### AD6: Issue Tracking (Beads Replacement)\n564\t\n565\t**Problem:** Beads is removed but the underlying need remains — retro findings, bugs, and tech debt need a path from \"discovered\" to \"scheduled\" to \"implemented.\" BMAD handles planned stories well but not unplanned issues.\n566\t\n567\t**Decision:** Simple `issues.yaml` file parallel to `sprint-status.yaml`.\n568\t\n569\t```yaml\n570\t# .codeharness/issues.yaml (or _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/issues.yaml)\n571\tissues:\n572\t  - id: issue-001\n573\t    title: Docker timeout handling too aggressive\n574\t    source: retro-epic-15       # where it came from\n575\t    priority: high\n576\t    status: ready-for-dev       # same statuses as stories\n577\t  - id: issue-002\n578\t    title: Evaluator too lenient on API error codes\n579\t    source: manual\n580\t    priority: medium\n581\t    status: backlog\n582\t```\n583\t\n584\t**How it works:**\n585\t- `codeharness issue create \"title\" --priority high --source retro-epic-15` → adds to issues.yaml\n586\t- Retro workflow tags findings as `actionable: true` → auto-added to issues.yaml\n587\t- Workflow engine reads both `sprint-status.yaml` (stories) AND `issues.yaml` (issues)\n588\t- Issues interleaved into execution based on priority\n589\t- Same statuses, same execution path, same verification — the engine doesn't distinguish stories from issues\n590\t\n591\t**Rationale:** File-based, no external dependencies, beads-level simplicity. Everything goes through the workflow engine. No separate issue tracker to maintain. Retro findings get a mechanical path to implementation instead of rotting in markdown.\n592\t\n593\t**Implementation Priority:**\n594\t1. Beads cleanup (unblock everything — 12 files, surgical removal)\n595\t2. Legacy deletion (ralph/, hooks/, old verify/proof modules)\n596\t3. New modules in dependency order (state → parser → resolver → dispatch → engine → evaluator → circuit-breaker)\n597\t4. Command rework (run.ts, verify.ts, init.ts, status.ts)\n598\t5. Skills and plugin.json update\n599\t6. Integration tests\n600\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01Tuyo7ARsiRwTfcugHgbJ4e","session_id":"06dc1e0b-83a0-4950-9e66-ec9396bae461","uuid":"96eb7190-d4d7-4238-8b19-8a91bf317818","timestamp":"2026-04-02T11:25:58.201Z"}
