{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01EvrAndE3hBCMRDSZyVFiQa","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01FvNUrv4cbh9ci6BbNnfsMq","name":"Grep","input":{"pattern":"FR1|FR5|500ms|parse time|workflow.*pars|workflow.*YAML","path":"/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/planning-artifacts/prd-evaluator-redesign.md","output_mode":"content","-C":2,"head_limit":40},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2108,"cache_read_input_tokens":58709,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2108,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01Tuyo7ARsiRwTfcugHgbJ4e","session_id":"06dc1e0b-83a0-4950-9e66-ec9396bae461","uuid":"f3340130-b466-4f7e-9f05-c8b1bf238a56"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01FvNUrv4cbh9ci6BbNnfsMq","type":"tool_result","content":"32-This redesign replaces the current hardcoded execution loop and self-verification theater with three things:\n33-\n34:1. **A declarative workflow engine** that drives multi-agent execution. A YAML workflow definition specifies task states, transitions, per-task prompts, agent assignments, expected inputs/outputs, and session boundaries (fresh context vs. continuation). This replaces Ralph's 1000+ lines of bash orchestration with something configurable and clean. Execution uses the Claude Agent SDK (`@anthropic-ai/claude-agent-sdk`) — the official TypeScript API for programmatic Claude Code control.\n35-\n36-2. **A single adversarial verification pass** against the final built artifact. No per-story micro-verification. No session flags. No proof document regex parsing. One blind evaluator agent — no source code access, only Docker, observability, and documentation — exercises the final artifact subjectively and produces a structured JSON verdict. The evaluator reads ACs in user language and independently figures out how to test them.\n--\n127-### Risk Mitigation\n128-\n129:**Workflow engine complexity:** Loops could create infinite execution if the circuit breaker fails. **Mitigation:** Schema validation rejects malformed flows at parse time. Circuit breaker is the hard stop regardless of flow definition. Max iterations cap always enforced.\n130-\n131-**Evaluator quality:** Anthropic found that \"out of the box, Claude is a poor QA agent.\" The evaluator judges subjectively — it reads ACs and independently exercises the artifact, requiring evidence for every verdict. **Mitigation:** Structured JSON output forces evidence. Calibrate against known-broken artifacts. Log all evaluator sessions. Run multiple trials (pass^3 is the real metric). Iterate on the evaluator prompt across real projects.\n--\n139-### Journey 1: First Run (Happy Path)\n140-\n141:Alex has a BMAD sprint plan with 8 stories for a Node.js API. Runs `codeharness init`, then `codeharness run`. No workflow YAML to write — the default handles it.\n142-\n143-The dev agent implements each story in a fresh session. After all 8 complete, the blind evaluator spawns — no source access, only Docker, observability endpoints, and story ACs. It independently figures out how to exercise each AC — makes real HTTP requests, checks DB state, queries traces. Verdict: 7/8 pass. Finding for AC5: \"POST /users returns 201 but doesn't persist — `docker exec psql -c 'SELECT count(*) FROM users'` returns 0.\"\n--\n206-After a sprint, Alex runs the retrospective. The retro produces three findings:\n207-1. \"Docker timeout too aggressive — evaluator killed mid-verification\" (actionable)\n208:2. \"Good: workflow YAML was easy to customize\" (not actionable)\n209-3. \"Evaluator didn't test error paths — only happy path\" (actionable)\n210-\n--\n230-### Journey 6: Engine Execution Flow\n231-\n232:Engine reads workflow YAML (resolved through embedded → user → project patches) and sprint-status.yaml:\n233-\n234-1. For each `per-story` task in flow order: resolve agent config (embedded → user → project patches) → compile to SDK inline subagent → generate trace ID → spawn session (fresh or continue) → pass input contract → collect output\n--\n251-### API Surface — Workflow YAML Schema\n252-\n253:The workflow YAML is the primary API surface:\n254-- Formally specified with a JSON schema\n255-- Validatable via `codeharness validate`\n--\n327-### Workflow Definition\n328-\n329:- FR1: User can define a workflow as a YAML file with tasks, flow order, and loop blocks\n330-- FR2: User can specify per-task properties: agent assignment, scope (per-story/per-run), session boundary (fresh/continue), source access, input/output contracts, and prompt template\n\n[Showing results with pagination = limit: 40]"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01Tuyo7ARsiRwTfcugHgbJ4e","session_id":"06dc1e0b-83a0-4950-9e66-ec9396bae461","uuid":"38ee5da4-7dd4-4060-8eea-d874141fe7b1","timestamp":"2026-04-02T11:26:25.240Z"}
